                    <p class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><span class="comment-author vcard"><a class="url fn" href="http://izbicki.me"   rel="external nofollow">Mike</a></span> on <span class="comment-permalink"><a title="Permalink to this comment" href="http://izbicki.me/blog/gausian-distributions-are-monoids#comment-955">November 25, 2012 at 9:35 AM</a></span>                    </p>
                    
                    <div class="comment-content content">
                        <p>I see what you mean, but I&#8217;m arguing that maybe mathematicians should have a much more general notion of what it means to be a &#8220;Gaussian distribution.&#8221;  We should be using the construct that is the most elegant, and this seems more elegant to me.</p>
<p>If I went the whole isomorphism route you suggest, I would have to add a couple of very pointless paragraphs explaining what all that means, and no one would slog through that to get to the juicier bits below.</p>
